#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:45
msgid "Layers Panel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:50
msgid "The :guilabel:`Layers` panel (also called the ``map legend``) lists all the layers in the project and helps you manage their visibility. You can show or hide it by pressing :kbd:`Ctrl+1`. A layer can be selected and dragged up or down in the legend to change the Z-ordering. Z-ordering means that layers listed nearer the top of the legend are drawn over layers listed lower down in the legend."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:57
msgid "The Z-ordering behavior can be overridden by the :ref:`Layer Order <layer_order>` panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:60
msgid "At the top of the Layers panel, a toolbar allows you to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:62
msgid "|symbology| :sup:`Open the layer styling dock (F7)`: toggle the layer styling panel on and off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:64
msgid "|addGroup| :sup:`Add new group`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:65
msgid "|showMapTheme| :sup:`Manage Map Themes`: control visibility of layers and arrange them in different map themes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:67
msgid "|filterMap| :sup:`Filter Legend by Map Content`: only the layers that are set visible and whose features intersect the current map canvas have their style rendered in the layers panel. Otherwise, a generic NULL symbol is applied to the layer. Based on the layer symbology, this is a convenient way to identify which kind of features from which layers cover your area of interest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:72
msgid "|expressionFilter| :sup:`Filter Legend by Expression`: apply an expression to remove styles from the selected layer tree that have no feature satisfying the condition. This can be used to highlight features that are within a given area/feature of another layer. From the drop-down list, you can edit and clear the expression currently applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:77
msgid "|expandTree| :sup:`Expand All` or |collapseTree| :sup:`Collapse All` layers and groups in the layers panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/user_manual/introduction/general_tools.rst:79
msgid "|removeLayer| :sup:`Remove Layer/Group` currently selected."
